target.value: 2009 baseline - 10% increase

actual.value: Proportion of visits referred to specialists = 25.71% for 2011, 22.18% for 9 months of 2012.Proportion of visits referred tohospitals = 1.82% for 2011, 1.52% for 9 months of 2012.

title.narrative: Increase utilization rates for primary health care for the general population (in Podgorica and outside Podgorica) and the Roma

baseline.value: 11.4% of population in Podgorica report use of PHC; 21% of Roma in Podgorica report use of PHC

target.value: Target groups (population in Podgorica, outside of Podgorica and Roma) report visiting their Chosen Doctor at or close to 40%

actual.value: NO UPDATED

title.narrative: PHC Patients are aware of and supportive of health reform

target.value: 70% or higher (nationally)

actual.value: 89% (nationally), from Integrity POS

title.narrative: Maintain or improve immunization rates (%) for DPT and measles (already high) following reform

baseline.value: DPT (initial and follow-up): 86% MMR (initial and follow-up): 82%

target.value: DPT (initial and follow-up): 94% MMR (initial and follow-up): 92%

actual.value: DPT (initial and follow-up): 94.7%MMR (initial and follow-up): 90.7%

comment.narrative: Partially achievedRevision possible - IPH to clarify whether the 2011 data is for Podgorica or nation-wide; IPH also to try torefine the data/change the denominators)

title.narrative: Operational health information systems in HIF, primary health care providers, pharmaceutical supply chain, to provide timely, accurate data on key elements of performance (expenditure, service utiliza

baseline.value: HIF Pharma and Insuree Register System Operational

target.value: Information system between HIF, primary health care providers and pharmaceutical supply chain continue to be operational. ITsystemfor drugs includes both public and private provider prescribed drugs. The information system connecting the HIF andhospitals, providing among other things information on the coding and costs related necessary to develop out-put based financed ie(DRGs), is launched.

actual.value: Information system between HIF, primary health care providers and pharmaceutical supply chain continues to be operational. HIF hasstarted elecontric invoicing and developed business information system within general hospitals nationwide. Special Hospitals ISunder development. DRG reporting begun in Sep 2012. IS components for MoH, IPH and Drug's Agency under development. Only privatedentists' practices integrated into the IS.

title.narrative: HIF increases its capacity to perform its functions of pooling health resources; better allocating health resources; and contracting providers towards improved performance

baseline.value: HIF in existence and developing improved control over pharmaceutical expenditures through pricing and information system withpharmacists

target.value: HIF has developed the necessary groundwork for developing hospital budgets based on output (i.e. DRGs) rather than inputsincludingdefining state-financed services, developing the information base, establishing a system of coding of diagnoses andgrouping of diagnoses appropriate for Montenegro, and training of hospital staff. Additional contracts with private providerssigned.

actual.value: The MoH procured the AR-DRG full versionGrouper to be developed from HIF resources. Hospitals started reporting under DRG systembeginning Sep 2012. No. of trained hospital staff amounts to approx. 300 (293) from 7 general, 2 special hospitals and the ClinicalCenter. The training is on-going and will continue after the project closing. • Hospital information system introduced in 7general hospitals. • Additional contracts with private providers signed

title.narrative: Increase satisfaction for primary health care of the general population (in Podgorica and outside of Podgorica) and specifically for the Roma

baseline.value: In Podgorica, 62% of the population totally satisfied and 20% partially satisfied

target.value: In Podgorica, 70% of the population totally satisfied and 27% partially satisfied; for the population outside of Podgorica, 66% ofthe population totally satisfied and 31% partially satisfied; and satisfaction of the Roma population remains high (i.e. 87.7% orhigher)

comment.narrative: The general population target should be slightly changed since based on HH survey, not public opinion survey. Will be discussedduring mission in May.

actual.value: In Podgorica, 77% satisfied or higher and 19% partially satisfied. Nationally, 70% satisfied or higher and 24% partiallysatisfied.Data from Integrity POS. No updated POS or HH survey data.

title.narrative: Adoption of bylaws and administrative documents covering health insurance, health care and pharmaceuticals

baseline.value: Laws on Health Insurance, Health Care and Pharmaceuticals in Draft

target.value: Laws maintained, including additional sub-regulations for pharmaceuticals

actual.value: 11 new laws adopted or amended. 4 new bylaws adopted. 434 Pharmaceutical drugs approved with 4 new subregulations. New Law onMedicines passed to meet EU regulations. Law on Health Care amended. Law on Health Insurance amended to include supplementalinsurance.

title.narrative: Revision of policy, benefits, and standards for primary care

baseline.value: Montenegro system of PHC inherited from former Yugoslavia

target.value: PHC Policies (particularly the payment mechanism and care protocols) refined based on implementation

actual.value: Payment mechanism continues to be fully operational. 11 Clinical protocols and guidelines developed for most frequent and mostcostly diseases, 10 of which through AF MHSIP activities.

title.narrative: Proposal developed for the appropriate quality assurance system in Montenegro

target.value: Proposal well developed, including lessons learned from the region and addresses the legal, institutional, financial and technicalaspects of a quality assurance system

actual.value: National Strategy for Improvement of Health Care Quality and Safety of Patients adopted in February 2012.

title.narrative: Drugs Agency developed to better perform its functions of regulating and ensuring the quality of drugs in Montenegro

target.value: Drugs Agency functional as a regulatory agency Drugs Agency has registered 10-15% of total drugs available on the market

actual.value: Drugs Agency has registered 44.5% (2011) of total drugs available on the market in Montenegro

title.narrative: Development of the reform for revision of policy, benefits and standards for secondary and tertiary care

target.value: Masterplan developed and adopted; benefit package of HIF-financed secondary and tertiary care services defined; and theinformationbase for developing an output (i.e. DRG) based financing model established

actual.value: Master Plan 2010-2013 adopted. Decision on Network of Health institutions adopted; Secondary and Tertiary HC Strategy adopted andpublished on MOH website. Hospital information system introduced in 7 general hopistals. DRG reporting begun in Sep 2012. BBP workinprogress. 11 Clinical protocols and guidelines developed.

title.narrative: Family Medicine specialization established and operational at Medical Faculty

target.value: Family Medicine Specialization to be established and initial cohort of students to be enrolled

actual.value: Family Medicine Additional Specialization Program developed, and first cohort of mentors to pass the final/specialist exam in Nov2012. Family Medicine Full Specialization Program developed, and the first cohort enrolled in Oct 2012

title.narrative: Number of PHC Teams (1 Chosen Doctor + 1 Nurse) provided retraining in family Medicine Nationally

target.value: Retraining Program Completed with a total of 255 teams (1 Doctor + 1 Nurse) retrained.

actual.value: Retraining Program Total of 273 teams and additional 6 nurses retrained (of which 248 teams and additional 31 nurses providedretraining in Family Medicine, and 25 specialists to pass the final/specialist exam in Family Medicine Additional SpecializationProgram,in Nov 2012).

title.narrative: HIF controls the increasing cost of nationally financed pharmaceuticals and medical materials

baseline.value: Share of HIF expenditures spent on drugs: 19.2% Share of HIF expenditures spent on drugs and medical materials: 28.4% HIF not yetanalyzing pharmaceutical expenditures

target.value: Over time, the HIF has expanded the list of drugs so overall costs may rise even with reductions in drug prices. Due to theeconomic crisis and changes in excha nge rates for imported drugs, reasonable 2012 targets are: Share of HIF expenditures spent ondrugs ator below 18.0% Share of HIF expenditures spent on drugs and medical materials at or below 27.5%

actual.value: Share of HIF expenditures spent on drugs: 20.0%Share of HIF expenditures spent on drugs and medical materials: 28.0%Totalexpenditures: 175,357,332.58 eur.

title.narrative: MoH stewardship of the health system improves as measured by increases of health related information and development of key health policies

baseline.value: The Strategy for Health Care Development in Montenegro until 2020 (2003) approved; basic health system laws in draft; Montenegroinunion with Serbia and not yet with own country laws and regulations

target.value: Secondary and Tertiary Care Reform Strategy developed and approved, including legislative framework for entering into publicprivate partnerships in health; Further refine PHC policies; new masterplan adopted

actual.value: nformation available: PHC Operational Review - Efficiency Study data available. Health System Integrity Assessment Report(WHO/UNDP) developed. Policy Developments: • Health Development Master Plan 2010-2013 adopted. • Law on Record Keeping inHealth adopted.Law on Health Care amended. Law on Health Insurance amended. • Decision on Network of Health institutions adopted;Secondary and Tertiary HC Strategy adopted by Government and published on the MOH website. • New Strategy for Quality Assuranceapproved in Feb 2012. • Total of 11 Clinical Protocols and Guidelines developed

target.value: 20 of 20 equipped with computer equipment 20 of 20 equipped with medical equipment
